  1. Create a missingness indicator for the variables gen, phb and tv.
new_boys <- boys %>% 
  mutate(mis_gen = is.na(gen), mis_phb = is.na(phb), mis_tv = is.na(tv))
  1. Assess whether missingness in the variables gen, phb and tv is related to someones age.
new_boys %>% 
  group_by(mis_gen) %>% 
  summarize(age = mean(age))
new_boys %>% 
  group_by(mis_phb) %>% 
  summarize(age = mean(age))
new_boys %>% 
  group_by(mis_tv) %>% 
  summarize(age = mean(age))
  1. Create a histogram for the variable age, faceted by whether or not someone has a missing value on gen.
new_boys %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~mis_gen)

Regression visualization

  1. Load the data elastic1 and elastic2 and bind the data frames together using the function bind_rows() and add a grouping variable indicating whether an observation comes from elastic1 or from elastic2.
elastic <- bind_rows("elastic1" = elastic1, "elastic2" = elastic2, .id = "Group")
  1. Create a scatterplot mapping stretch on the x-axis and distance on the y-axis, and map the just created group indicator as the color aesthetic.
elastic %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=stretch, y=distance, colour=Group)) +
  geom_point()

13. Recreate the previous plot, but now assess whether the results of the two data sets appear consistent by adding a linear regression line.

elastic %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=stretch, y=distance, colour=Group)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

14. For each of the data sets elastic1 and elastic2, fit a regression model with y = distance on x = stretch using lm(y ~ x, data).

lm1 <- lm(distance ~ stretch, elastic1)
lm2 <- lm(distance ~ stretch, elastic2)
  1. For both of the previously created fitted models, determine the fitted values and the standard errors of the fitted values, and the proportion explained variance R2.

  1. Use the elastic2 variable stretch to obtain predictions on the model fitted on elastic1.
pred <- predict(lm1, elastic2)
  1. Now make a scatterplot to investigate similarity between the predicted values and the observed values for elastic2.
new_stretch <- data.frame(stretch = c(elastic2$stretch, elastic2$stretch), 
                          distance = c(pred,elastic2$distance),
                          group = as.factor(c(rep('P', length(pred)),rep('A', length(elastic2$stretch)))))
